<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / London Stock Exchange: ICI and Zeneca firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This year's headline demerger ended 1993 on a positive note with ICI rising
against the market to close 11 up at 802p and Zeneca lifting 8 to 842p.
US buyers had pushed ICI higher in New York on Wednesday night after they
bought the shares in the form of American Depositary Receipts - ICI ADRs in
New York were up Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 47 1/2 before Wall Street opened
yesterday. The rise squeezed the London stock higher.
Analysts said the shares also benefited from the deal announced by Shell and
Montedison for a merger of their polyolefins interests deal due to 'hopes
for further consolidation in the chemicals industry'.
However dealers attributed much of the strength in the two stocks two heavy
buying from Swiss Bank Corporation which was involved in the expiry of a
very large tailor made option, said to cover 30 leading stocks. One senior
marketmaker said 'Swiss Bank had the ball and they wouldn't let anyone else
play with it.'
High street retailers were broadly lower as institutions moved in to lock in
some of the big profits in the sector.
