<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Christmas and New Year holidays are having their usual effect on the
market. No wool sales are held, and at the same time most firms in the main
wool using countries are closed not only for production but also for trading
purposes, with only skeleton staffs nominally available. Since the market
itself closed before Christmas with prices either barely steady or only
hesitantly firmer, buying incentives are in any case limited. Only with
certain British wool categories was there a definite price rise, and this
was due to a very small number of firms competing to fill special needs. As
for the market, when it does revive after the holiday, wait and see seems to
be the general approach.
</TEXT>
