<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Zambian copper group pulls back
from brink, says Credit Lyonnais
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUSAKA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines, the country's biggest export earner and
once one of the world's biggest copper producers, has in the past few weeks
pulled back from threatened collapse, caused by a cash-flow crisis, and 1994
could provide ideal conditions for the state-owned group 'to turn positively
to the task of renewal and revival,' according to Credit Lyonnais Laing,
part of the French banking group.
CLL suggests that a weakening copper price and a strong local currency swept
ZCCM's profits away in the second half of the financial year that ends next
March.
'The fall in the copper price in the second half of 1993 exposed the
high-cost nature of the operations on the (African) copper belt and also
exposed the problems of a reactive management which has done too little to
cut long-term costs and which has yet to come to terms with new hardline
government policy on industrial support,' says analyst Mr Michael Coulson in
CLL's latest International Mining Monitor.
He suggests that at present ZCCM is not generating enough cash to service
repayments on its near-USDollars 900m of debt or to maintain output at
present operations, let alone to allow investment in the development of new
mines to secure its future.
'If nothing is done, the best ZCCM could hope for would be a future of
steady decline with the occasional metal price surge enabling the company to
undertake some new project development but on a much smaller scale than
originally envisaged,' says Mr Coulson. This would mean annual output of
200,000 tonnes for 15 to 20 years whereas the present USDollars 2bn, 14-year
plan would continue output at about 450,000 tonnes for 50 years.
He calls for the Zambian government to move forward with privatisation of
ZCCM, something donors of the country's USDollars 7bn debt believe would
strengthen Zambia's economic performance.
Mr Coulson dismisses, however, the idea that ZCCM - which has a present
stock market value of about USDollars 300m - is worth billions. This idea
harks back to the early 1980s when the oil groups were bidding up the price
of mining companies and the Japanese offered USDollars 2bn for Zambia's
copper mines.
He says that, ideally, an additional big mining group should get involved
with ZCCM alongside the Anglo American Corporation of South Africa, which
owns 27.3 per cent. Anglo will have a great deal to do in 'courting the new
ANC-dominated (South African) government.' It would be healthy for a big
group such as RTZ Corporation of the UK, Phelps Dodge of the US or BHP of
Australia to enter the picture, perhaps by taking a majority stake in the
USDollars 550m, Konkola Deep mine venture that is vital to ZCCM's long-term
plans.
Mr Coulson concludes: 'We do not think disaster for ZCCM is inevitable. The
reconstruction and refinancing of the company swiftly undertaken can secure
its competitive position in the international copper market and underpin its
long-term future as a substantial and low-cost producer'.
ZCCM is threatening Zambia's budget and economic reform programme by failing
to pay taxes and debts, according to a senior government mining official,
reports Reuter from Lusaka.
</TEXT>
