<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / International Company News: Troubled German group to meet
banks next week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Metallgesellschaft, the troubled Frankfurt-based conglomerate, has brought
forward a planned meeting with its bankers to discuss the full extent of its
liquidity problems.
Frankfurt bankers said yesterday that preliminary talks between the company
and leading bankers had taken place in New York this week. Following these
talks Mr Kajo Neukirchen, Metallgesellschaft's chief executive, decided to
invite all its bank creditors to a meeting on Tuesday or Wednesday of next
week, bringing the date forward from January 10.
The fact that the meeting will take place earlier than expected indicates
the group's problems are more serious than expected, bankers said.
But Metallgesellschaft refused to comment yesterday on an advance report
from the next issue of the Spiegel news magazine that Mr Neukirchen would
seek a full-scale moratorium on group debt estimated at a gross DM8bn
(Dollars 4.6bn) in order to stave off insolvency.
Metallgesellschaft, a conglomerate with activities ranging from mining and
metals to engineering and raw materials trading, said management was working
intensively on 'damage control and possibilities for a solution' to problems
which had arisen through the oil trading activities of MG Corp, its US
trading subsidiary. Details would be presented to bankers next week, the
company added.
Commenting on the report in the Spiegel, Metallgesellschaft said the DM8bn
level of indebtedness applied to the group as a whole, was offset by
considerable liquid resources, and was not unusual for a group which derived
around half its annual turnover of DM27bn from trading activities.
Full details of Metallgesellschaft's indebtedness have not been disclosed -
the group has not published a balance sheet for the financial year to
September 1993.
Mr Heinz Schimmelbusch said in November, before he was ousted as chief
executive, that the ratio of equity to debt was 20 per cent.
Metallgesellschaft's liquidity problems, which led earlier this month to the
forced departure of Mr Schimmelbusch and five further board directors, stem
from the oil futures trading activities of MG Corp on the New York
Mercantile Exchange (Nymex).
No details have been released but it seems likely that MG Corp contracted
forward to buy up to 160m barrels of oil in anticipation of rising oil
prices. But sharply falling oil prices have triggered steep margin calls -
cash payouts - with Nymex which are not necessarily covered by hedging
arrangements.
The cash payouts forced Mr Schimmelbusch to turn to bankers to solve what
were then described as temporary liquidity problems.
Lex, Page 12
</TEXT>
