<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Options scramble behind FT-SE moves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The expiry of some Pounds 4bn of over-the-counter options (OTCs) has been
one of the main factors behind sharp movements in the London stock market
over the past two days.
A prime reason for the surge which took the FT-SE 100 index to a peak of
3,480.8 yesterday was share buying by investment funds and banks to cover
their OTC positions.
Many funds have been buying 'bespoke puts', which give an option to sell the
underlying market at a fixed time and price, and selling calls, to lock in
profits made earlier in the year. Few fund managers, however, were able to
allow for the latest rise which has lifted the stock market by about 9 per
cent since the November 30 Budget.
The principal expiry yesterday involved an institution which had bought a
'zero cost collar', an OTC covering call options and put options in about 30
leading Footsie stocks. It was one of a number of OTC deals, mostly carried
out by Swiss Bank Corporation, which have expired this week.
Once the positions were covered, buying pressure eased yesterday and
profit-taking took the FT-SE 100 to 3,428.8, down 33.2 on the day.
Mr Chris Salter, head of UK trading at SBC, said: 'The OTC market has really
picked up in London this year and we have carried out a large percentage of
the recent transactions.'
Morgan Stanley, Goldman Sachs, Salomon Brothers and UBS have also been
providing OTC insurance against falls in the market for US income funds, UK
investment funds, UK life assurance funds and some pension groups.
Mr Guru Ramakrishnan, derivatives specialist at Morgan Stanley, the US
investment bank, said: 'I am continually astounded by the increasing number
of accounts using OTCs, but they do offer considerable flexibility and
anonymity at a fair price.'
The main difference between traded options dealt on the London International
Financial Futures Exchange and OTCs is that OTCs are secret - only the
seller (writer) and buyer are aware of the details because they are not
traded through an exchange.
They are also more flexible than traded options having an expiry price and
maturity date that can be agreed by the two parties involved. The main
criticism is that it is difficult to make a market, but supporters say that
for any one OTC there are around half a dozen participants prepared to make
a price.
Awareness of OTCs has grown considerably this year, along with the use of
derivative products generally. Although there are no figures available
because of the anonymous nature of the market, dealers estimate that the
nominal value of OTCs on the FT-SE 100 index runs into billions of pounds.
Some derivatives analysts say there could be further volatility in today's
end-of-year half session as another large OTC option expires.
European futures, Page 17; London market, Back Page
</TEXT>
