<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The last night of the year has become one of the prime moments for avoiding
television if you can, but today, if you pick your way through the
schedules, you should be able to avoid all that ghastly false merriment.
Starting at 7.55pm BBC2 offers a performance of La Traviata recorded in La
Fenice, Venice, one of the most charming opera houses in Italy, though
small. Coloratura soprano Edita Gruberova sings Violetta, the doomed
courtesan, tenor Neil Shicoff is Alfredo, and baritone Giorgio Germont takes
the part of his namesake Giorgio. Direction for television is by Derek
Bailey, one of the best in the world, with staging and design by Pier Luigi
Pizzi, and the orchestra and chorus of the Fenice is under Carlo Rizzi. A
treat.
When that ends at 10.05pm Channel 4 will be just 15 minutes into its New
Year's Eve Triple Whammy which manages to celebrate the new year three times
by stationing cameras in Cape Town (new year at 10pm GMT) Prague (11pm) and
Dublin (midnight). With luck this should avoid all traces of heather and fat
men reading gags off autocue.
</TEXT>
