<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / 1993 in Review:  ..The Downside - Quotes of the year
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
'I've rigged enough meetings to know how it's done' - Corporate PR
consultant Brian Basham.
'You're predicating this on an 'if' basis.' John Major
'I would not set foot in the sea except to recover a deckchair'. Mr Alan
Hall, Blackpool deck chair attendant.
'An angel at night whispered to me in the wind and told me there is no such
thing as an angel whispering to you in the wind'. Jacques Attali's parting
words to EBRD staff.
'People from business are invariably a nuisance when it comes to talking
about the economy'. Prof Patrick Minford, one of the chancellor's 'seven
wise men'.
'Je ne regrette rien'. Norman Lamont
'In your house, if you want to do it, you have the legal right to answer
everybody that comes to your door with a gun.' Lewis Unglby, defence
attorney, winning acquittal for Louisiana man who shot dead a 16-year-old
Japanese student who inadvertently rang the wrong doorbell and did not
understand 'freeze]'
'How does a working class town of 100,000 people come to terms with there
being no work when the whole culture is based on work?' Dr David Clark,
Labour MP for South Shields.
'We shouldn't have to sacrifice a single job in Lorraine to save a job in
Bohemia'. Mr Dominique Strauss-Kahn, French industry minister.
Michael Heseltime is 'more like a lemming every day. Not content with
digging himself into a hole on coal, it now appears that he is jumping
headlong into a pickle on the Post Office'. Shadow trade and industry
secretary Robin Cook.
'You are simply being a lickspittle for the Establishment - that's why you
are trooped out so often'. Sun editor Kelvin MacKenzie to Tory MP Sir Ivan
Lawrence.
</TEXT>
