<DATE>931231
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Business failures decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of business failures fell this year for the first time since
1988, with the biggest declines in London, Wales and the east Midlands,
according to figures from Dun &amp; Bradstreet, the business information
company.
The report indicates small companies are finding it harder to climb out of
recession than big ones, but finds further signs that the recovery is
becoming better established.
The total for companies going into liquidation or becoming bankrupt in
England and Wales fell 11.5 per cent in the final quarter of this year
compared with the corresponding period last year. There was a 19.8 per cent
yearly decline in the third quarter.
The figures show that the worst places for small businesses appear to be the
west Midlands and north-west and north-east England, which all saw slight
increases in small-business failures over the year.
Total business failures in 1993 came to 48,066, down 7.5 per cent on the
51,947 registered last year. This compares with a 30.4 per cent rise in
collapses last year from 39,827 in 1991. This year's figure is roughly twice
that for 1990, the start of the recession, and is well above the peak in
failures during the 1980s of 21,682, recorded in 1984. Part of the reason
for the large number of collapses in recent years is that many of the new
companies which mushroomed during the late 1980s boom encountered financial
difficulties during the recession.
Liquidations of large limited companies fell 14.4 per cent this year to
19,220, from 22,444 last year, while bankruptcies of small businesses fell
by only 2.3 per cent, to 28,846. In the fourth quarter of this year, total
business collapses came to 11,863, down on the 13,397 recorded in the final
three months of last year. This last figure was the highest quarterly number
of failures during the period of low economic growth. Failures in the fourth
quarter of this year were slightly higher than the particularly low 10,320
collapses in the third quarter, though comfortably down on the 13,235
between April and June.
In Scotland, collapses totalled 7,667 this year after 10,820 last year.
However the figures are distorted by changes in Scots bankruptcy laws
introduced this year. In the UK, excluding Northern Ireland, failures
totalled 55,733, down 11.2 per cent last year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
