<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Christmas lift for book sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Book publishers have had their best Christmas for at least three years,
according to a study by market research group MarketLine International,
Raymond Snoddy writes.
The retail value of books sold in the UK last year was Pounds 2.52bn, a
figure which is estimated to rise to Pounds 2.7bn this year and Pounds
2.95bn in 1994.
Consumers spent Pounds 1.7bn on books this year, almost 5 per cent of all
recreational spending with every man, women and child buying an average of
seven books each.
Sixty-seven per cent of revenue comes from consumer books, 25 per cent from
academic and professional and 8 per cent from school books.
The volume of book sales is expected to rise to 405m copies next year from
401m this. There is no sign of a drop in reading, despite increased
competition from electronic media.
UK Books Report 1993-94. MarketLine International, 16 Connaught St, London
W2 2AF. Pounds 145.
