<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Arms sales to Serbia denied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Heckler &amp; Koch, a subsidiary of the UK armaments manufacturer, Royal
Ordnance, yesterday denied allegations that it had illegally supplied small
arms to Serbia in contravention of arms embargoes.
The allegations are the latest twist to reports that throughout the 1980s,
Heckler &amp; Koch and Royal Ordnance - which bought the German concern in 1991
 -were part of an international cartel illegally selling arms to a variety
of countries.
In developments apart from the Serbian arms sales allegation, Mr Walter
Lamp, the former manager director of Heckler &amp; Koch, is to be tried in
Germany on charges that Heckler &amp; Koch in conjunction with Royal Ordnance
diverted arms through the UK to illegal destinations such as Nicaragua and
Iraq.
The mention of Iraq as a destination has lead the Scott arms-to-Iraq enquiry
office in London to admit that it will be investigating allegations arising
from the German trial.
Meanwhile, Customs and Excise yesterday strongly denied reports that it has
supplied documents backing claims that Iran may also have been a beneficiary
of explosives sales channelled through the UK by Royal Ordnance.
A Customs official yesterday insisted no such documents had ever been passed
over to the department's investigators.
The Scott enquiry also denied the report, saying all Customs documents
relevant to the probe were handed over before Mr Justice Scott began his
inquiry.
</TEXT>
