<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Italy's Inflation continues to fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's annualised inflation rate fell to 4 per cent in December, the lowest
level in 24 years, writes Robert Graham. According to Istat, the national
statistics office, consumer prices registered zero growth in December, as
part of a continuing downward trend in the overall level of inflation. The
potential inflationary effects of the devaluation of the lira have been
offset by depressed domestic demand. Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the prime
minister, predicted earlier this week that inflation could be at an
annualised rate of 2.5 per cent by the end of 1994.
