<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Kohl takes a sober view of the new year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl today said Germany was moving out of recession, but
tempered his optimistic forecasts for the new year with warnings of more
spending cut-backs, and a slow recovery in the labour market.
In his annual new year's eve television address, and an article in the
end-of-year issue of Handelsblatt, the economics daily, Mr Kohl identified
unemployment as the most worrying single issue among Germans.
By the end of the year, 8.7 per cent of the labour force, or 3.44m people
will be unemployed - the highest levels since the second world war. They
include 2.28m from western Germany and over 1.16m from the eastern states.
Mr Kohl said a package of radical reforms at the work - place was needed to
help guarantee existing jobs, create new ones, and improve Germany's
competitiveness.
'Securing the future forces us to make more cuts. . . what we need is
courage and realism, initiative and confidence,' he said.
In a sober broadcast, and reflective article, the chancellor gave priority
to domestic issues, instead of focusing on European Union affairs as in
previous speeches this year. The shift reflected his agenda for next year's
marathon round of state and parliamentary elections.
Mr Kohl insisted that the government's two-track strategy of reforms in
western Germany and large financial transfers to eastern Germany would
ultimately create jobs and counteract the social costs of unification. But
he warned that even after the recovery it would 'take a considerably longer
time until positive aspects are felt on the labour market'.
He explained that one of the reasons for Germany's lack of competitiveness,
and consequent high unemployment, was a sense of delusion about the
effectiveness of the country's social and economic structures, which
postponed any fundamental discussion about reforms. 'The creation of 3m jobs
over the past years tempted us into believing there was no need to become
more competitive,' he said.
He added that the recipe for competitiveness hinged on the workplace, a
theme the government has constantly repeated over the past year. He said
reforms would include 'flexibility in working hours, and particularly more
job sharing', underpinned by reducing costs.
</TEXT>
