<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Job scene improves in France
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The rise in French unemployment slowed sharply in November, increasing by
3,200 to 3.29m, the labour ministry announced yesterday. The unemployment
rate at the end of the month was stable at 12 per cent of the workforce.
A ministry official said the figures showed the effects of government
measures to encourage training schemes and part-time employment. But he said
that the rate of unemployment was likely to increase further.
This view was echoed by private sector economists. 'The rate of increase has
slackened but we are likely to see further rises in unemployment until the
second half of next year,' said Mr Paul O'Brien, economist at Morgan
Guaranty.
The slowing in the rise of unemployment in November partly reflected a
reduced number of job losses in the services sector. Economists said that it
also represented a correction from the sharp increase in October, when the
rate jumped from 11.8 per cent to 12 per cent.
November's unemployment figures are the latest in a series of statistics
which suggest that the economy has endured the worst of its sharp recession.
Mr Edmond Alphandery, economy minister, argues that the economy is now
stabilising and is due to expand by about 1.4 per cent next year in terms of
gross domestic product.
The French environment minister, Mr Michel Barnier, yesterday called for an
extraordinary EU meeting to review sea transport rules following the
littering of France's western coast by explosives and pesticides washed up
on shore, Reuter reports from Paris.
</TEXT>
