<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Industrial leaders and MPs dominate new year honours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Politicians, captains of industry and top civil servants have again
dominated the leading awards in the New Year's Honours List, despite the
prime minister's recent call for a broader range of individuals to be
decorated.
As part of his mission to create a 'classless society', Mr John Major said
that the biannual honours lists should increasingly reflect exceptional
achievement rather than status, with more awards going to people who have
done voluntary work and fewer to state servants.
However, although this new year's list contains a larger number of awards
for voluntary workers than previously, most of the top decorations have
again gone to leading public figures and company chief executives.
Moreover, less than a quarter of the list is made up of individuals who have
been nominated by a member of the public, under a scheme launched by the
prime minister in March.
Downing Street officials said yesterday that the public had recommended
about 7,500 individuals for a decoration. But only 200 of the 900 awards
made today were backed by the public - and in only 70 cases were awards
generated solely by an external nomination. Officials said they were still
scrutinising about 4,000 of the original nominations, but they expected the
number to increase in future years. The awards to industrialists reflect a
greater admiration for Britain's established companies rather than for the
acquisitive conglomerates singled out in Lady Thatcher's honours lists in
the 1980s.
Mr Iain Vallance, the chairman of BT, is one of five leading business
figures to receive a knighthood. The others are Mr Michael Perry, the
chairman of Unilever, Mr Richard Sykes, chief executive of Glaxo Holdings,
Mr Brian Pearse, chief executive of the Midland Bank and Mr Ian Wood,
managing director of John Wood group, an offshore oil company regarded as
one of Scotland's fastest growing corporations.
Sir David Nickson, chairman of the Clydesdale Bank and former president of
the Confederation of British Industry, is one of only two new life peers in
the list. The other is Sir Patrick Wright, a former head of the Diplomatic
Service.
Mr Archie Hamilton, the former minister for the armed forces and a former
parliamentary private secretary to Lady Thatcher, is one of three MPs to be
knighted for political service. The other two are Mr Peter Fry, Tory MP for
Wellingborough, and Mr David Madel, Tory MP for Bedfordshire South West.
Mr Kenneth Warren, former Tory MP and chairman of the all-party trade and
industry select committee, also receives a knighthood. Mr Gus O'Donnell, the
prime minister's press secretary who is due to leave next year, is made a
Companion of the Order of the Bath. The Labour party has again not put
forward any MPs in protest at the system.
Leading the awards in the world of arts are Dame Janet Baker, the opera
singer, who is made a Companion of Honour and Mr Derek Jacobi, the actor,
who is knighted.
Honours list in detail, Page 5
A matter of national honour, Page 11
</TEXT>
