<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow advances as new year is
awaited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
For the second consecutive day US share prices traded close to their opening
values as dealers and investors waited for the holiday week to end and a new
trading year to start in earnest, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 0.56 at 3,794.33, a
new record high. The more broadly based Standard&amp; Poor's 500 finished down
0.36 at 470.58. Secondary indices put in a more robust performance, with the
Amex composite ending up 2.16 at 472.16, and the Nasdaq composite up 3.92 at
768.48. Trading volume was 283m shares. Prices firmed at the start as
investors reacted to more positive news on the economy. The good news was a
0.5 per cent increase in the November leading economic indicators, and a 29
per cent rise in November existing home sales. The data was sufficient to
push the Dow close to 3,800, but by mid-morning, weakness among oil stocks,
notably Chevron and Exxon, brought the Dow back from its early highs.
The strengthening economy, combined with low interest rates and the
expectation that share prices would end the year on a positive note as they
usually do, were all working in the market's favour, and keeping stocks at
or close to record highs.
The selling in the oil sector was the main story in a featureless day,
although the declines were not widespread. Exxon fell Dollars  3/8 at
Dollars 63&lt;5/8, Chevron Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 88, and British Petroleum,
Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 64 3/4 , some oil stocks escaped the sell-off.
Phillips Petroleum rose Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 29 1/8 , and Mobil rose
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 79 1/8 . The latter was probably helped by the news
that the company had sold off four pipeline systems, closed 10 product
storage terminals and cut its domestic marine fleet by 33 per cent as part
of a year-long streamlining of its US distribution system.
Airline stocks underperformed after the brokerage house, Prudential
Securities, cut its rating of Delta Air Lines stock from 'buy' to 'hold'.
Delta fell Dollars 1 to Dollars 54 5/8 , UAL gave up Dollars 2 1/8 at
Dollars 146, AMR, parent of American Airlines, slipped Dollars 1/2 to
Dollars 67 3/8 , while USAir eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 12 3/4 .
CompUSA jumped Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 20 3/4 on the news that the
technology goods retailer's same-store sales had risen 13 per cent in its
second fiscal quarter.
On the Nasdaq market, Intel gave up some of Tuesday's gains, slipping
Dollars 7/8 to Dollars 63 1/8. Other big technology stocks were also weaker,
with Apple down Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 28 1/2, and Microsoft off Dollars 1
1/4 at Dollars 81 1/2.
Canada
Toronto stocks hit a record high in continued light trading. The TSE-300
composite index gained 21.07 points, or 0.49 per cent, to 4,309.92,
surpassing the previous record high of 4307.67 set on Dec. 8.
Advances led declines 408 to 269. Volume was 34.50m shares compared with
35.49m.
Hollinger's American Publishing Co. unit purchased 33 publications from Park
Communications Inc. for an undisclosed amount. Hollinger shares were
unchanged at CDollars 14. AGRA Industries reported much higher net income
from continuing operations in the first quarter. Its A shares fell CDollars
1/8 to CDollars 9 7/8.
</TEXT>
