<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / High street banks want card groups to join clearing body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
High street banks are to invite credit and debit card payment groups such as
Visa and Switch to join their body responsible for cheque and cash clearing.
An internal study has raised concerns about growing competition from payment
systems not run by banks.
The effort to bring credit and debit payments under the Association for
Payment Clearing Services umbrella follows the collapse of the banks'
attempt in the 1980s to create Eftpos, a single clearing and settlement
system for debit cards.
Since the collapse of the Eftpos initiative in 1989, the largest
co-operative effort involving credit and debit cards within Apacs has been
the joint initiative to reduce fraud. Card payments are now settled by rival
card groups, although they are cleared through banks.
After a study which has also led banks to allow mutual or sub-contracted
processing of cheques and credit vouchers to save costs, Apacs has now
decided to try to extend membership to outside clearing and payment groups,
notably the card payment organisations.
The unpublished study says it believes that 'there would be benefits to such
organisations from having a stronger relationship with Apacs, and that most
would wish to do so, provided the balance of rights and obligations was
sensible, and there was a level playing field'.
The study argues that the 'orderly development' of the payments industry is
fundamental to maintaining standards such as avoiding fraud. However, it
points out that the membership of international payments systems has
mushroomed in the past decade, leading to far greater diversity.
It predicts 'fierce competition' throughout the 1990s between the leading
payments systems and networks including Visa, Mastercard and the bank-owned
Swift international payments network, as well as third party processing
companies such as Sligos.
Apacs executives say they have no intention of trying to revive Eftpos,
which collapsed after the launch of Barclays' Connect debit card and the
formation of the Switch consortium.
Mr Andrew Malecki, head of strategy and planning, said there was 'zero
chance' of Apacs trying to set up a single national clearing and settlement
system for plastic cards.
Mr Malecki said Apacs' ruling council had approved the strategy set out in
the study of association of embracing 'a wide range of payment clearing and
settlement activities and organisations', but it had not set precise terms
for the admission of new members.
Some Apacs executives believe the association would have to admit card
groups on more flexible terms than in the past because organisations such as
Visa and Mastercard have international memberships, and constitutions which
would be difficult to change.
</TEXT>
