<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / US bank tries to distance itself from troubled partner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J P. Morgan has enjoyed a reputation for quality which is the envy of other
US bankers. So it was with interest - and not a little glee - that other US
financiers have watched the US's most prestigious bank become embroiled in
Banesto's difficulties.
In hard financial terms, the Spanish bank's problems will to have little
impact on J. P. Morgan. It is thought to have invested Dollars 17.5m
indirectly in the bank through the Corsair fund, a specialist limited
partnership it created to invest in bank stocks. But the fact that J. P.
Morgan, with its blue-chip reputation, was so closely linked with the bank
will have greater repercussions.
Banesto, an outsider in the Spanish banking establishment, did not appear a
natural partner for J. P. Morgan. 'This was not a Morganesque institution,'
said Mr George Salem, banking analyst at Prudential Securities.
A second concern has been the extent to which J. P. Morgan allowed itself to
become enmeshed in Banesto. This is likely to prompt questions about how the
bank handled possible conflicts of interest.
In February Corsair, a J. P. Morgan-sponsored bank 'vulture fund', took a
Dollars 175m stake in the bank. Such funds aim to buy shares in troubled
companies which they believe are undervalued and benefit from a share-price
rebound. Then, in the spring and summer, J. P. Morgan led international
equity issues for Banesto totalling about Dollars 775m. And Mr Robert
Mendoza, one of four J. P. Morgan vice-chairmen, had a seat on Banesto's
board.
J. P. Morgan appeared yesterday to be distancing itself from Corsair. One
financial institution which made inquiries of J. P. Morgan yesterday said
the bank disclaimed responsibility for the fund. 'They bragged about it when
they launched it, so they can't disown it now,' the institution said.
By denting J. P. Morgan's reputation, the Banesto debacle could hurt its
attempts to build an investment banking business. J. P. Morgan has been in
the van of US commercial banks seeking to extend their involvement into the
capital markets. It has only a small presence in the US underwriting
business, handling 3.2 per cent of corporate debt issues and 1.5 per cent of
equity issues this year, according to Securities Data. But its presence in
US capital markets is still more substantial than any other US commercial
bank.
Institutions like the GE pension fund and Northwestern Mutual Life, the
eighth-biggest US life company, were large holders in Banesto. The bank's
problems, coming so soon after J. P. Morgan promoted its shares, are likely
to harm the bank's relationships with such prominent US institutions.
While US investors are thought to have been among the biggest buyers of
Banesto's stock in rights issues led by J. P. Morgan this year, several
institutions said Banesto's problems would not affect their involvement in
international equity markets. The GE pension fund, with about 1.5 per cent
of the bank's stock, said it would not change its plans.
A portfolio of European bank stocks would still show a considerable gain
this year even after the Banesto problems, said Mr John Hickling, an
international portfolio manager with Fidelity Investments, the biggest US
mutual funds group.
'Clearly retail investors are throwing money at a lot of things - most
recently it's been the emerging markets funds. Those are the things that
really terrify me,' he added.
</TEXT>
