<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / SIB delays rules for disclosing commission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Securities and Invest-ments Board, the City's chief watchdog, has put on
hold plans to require sales agents to disclose commission on term-assurance
policies.
The SIB board has decided to leave the question for the new Personal
Investment Authority, the proposed super-regulator for personal financial
services which is due to start operating around the middle of next year.
But SIB did agree draft proposals to be submitted to the Treasury on how all
sales agents - independent advisers, authorised representatives and those
based at banks and building societies - should disclose to prospective
customers the commission on sales of life products.
Its decision on term assurance represents a slight setback in the overall
moves towards disclosure of commission in the selling of financial services,
and followed opposition from the industry.
As commissions for selling term-assurance policies are lower than those for
life insurance, disclosure was thought to be less controversial.
But because term assurance is taken out for protection rather than for
investment, and because policyholders surviving beyond the period of their
policies receive no payment, it falls outside the terms of SIB's remit from
the Treasury. To draw up rules on commission disclosure in this area, SIB
would require the co-operation of the industry.
The rules are expected to seek to ensure that those selling and providing
life products along with other financial services, such as selling an
endowment policy with a mortgage, are not able to evade the rules by
switching commission to the 'non-life' product.
SIB confirmed that the proposals were 'on ice', but made clear they were
expected to be adopted by the PIA.
The move will, however, delay their implementation. By the time the rules
have been completed, the requirement to disclose commission on life
insurance is not expected to be in effect much before the end of the year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
