<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / IoD urges union reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions should lose their legal protection and turn themselves into voluntary
bodies servicing the legal rights of individual workers, the Institute of
Directors said yesterday.
The IoD, which is preparing its evidence to the Commons employment committee
on the future of unions, believes ending all legal immunities would conclude
the strategy begun by the government 13 years ago.
The institute will tell the government that action is needed to ensure that
industrial relations remain good during the recovery and that there is no
return to excessive wage demands by public-sector unions.
The IoD's main aim is to convince the government that it should legislate
further over unions. It points out that additional legislation will be
needed by 1996 to insert European Union directives into UK labour law.
The IoD's proposals include:
The introduction of a comprehensive system of legal rights for individuals
governing contracts of employment. The IoD believes unions will be obsolete
as collective bargainers and it sees no reason why workers organised in
groups should have special privileges.
The removal of any right to strike and the abolition of legal immunities for
workers in essential services. It favours the introduction of a statutory
duty for such workers to maintain services with compensation paid if the
legal obligation is not fulfilled. This would cover workers in the health
service, gas, water, electricity, telephone operating, ambulance and fire
services.
The end of centralised pay bargaining in the public sector with the
abolition of the remaining public-sector pay review bodies and further use
of performance-related individual pay.
Restriction of picketing to only six strikers at an entrance to their
workplace, and the introduction of a statutory picketing code to replace the
present voluntary system. It proposes that all mass picketing be made
unlawful. The removal of the legal obligation on companies to give unions
information for collective bargaining purposes.
Measures to encourage companies to introduce employee share ownership and
profit-related pay schemes.
</TEXT>
