<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / Republicans demand more concessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELFAST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Republican opinion in Northern Ireland appears to be hardening against the
London-Dublin peace declaration, after a meeting of more than 300 activists
suggested that there was no support for the declaration in its current form.
The meeting, involving members of Sinn Fein and the IRA and other
republicans from across the province, in Loughmacrory, County Tyrone late on
Tuesday, provided the first public demonstration of attitudes among IRA and
Sinn Fein supporters towards the declaration, issued two weeks ago by Mr
John Major and Mr Albert Reynolds.
At the meeting, attended by some of the 60 IRA prisoners on Christmas
parole, speakers insisted that they wanted peace discussions, but that
further explanations and concessions were needed from the UK government
before the declaration could be endorsed. None of the speakers accepted the
declaration in its current form.
They indicated an amnesty for prisoners they regard as political prisoners
was essential for any agreement, though Mr Brendan McFarlane, an IRA
prisoner on parole, in-sisted the prisoners could not be used as a
bargaining chip.
Mr Richard McAuley, a Sinn Fein official, denied that the party had made a
decision on the declaration, although he said that 'on one level' the
meeting reflected the mood of the republican community.
'There is a sense of disappointment now that people have had a chance to
look at the document and listen to what has been said by British ministers,'
he said.
Sinn Fein claims that a process of consultation is continuing with its
members. But the main reason for the delayed response appears to be
tactical, with republicans hoping to extract further concessions from
London.
The Tyrone meeting is likely to increase pressure on Mr Gerry Adams, Sinn
Fein president, to toughen his stance.
The IRA's tactics were further underlined in its new year message to its
followers in the Republican News newspaper. In the message, the IRA insists
that it supports continuation of the broader peace process, but gives no
indication of any readiness to abandon violence.
</TEXT>
