FT  30 DEC 93 / Legal challenge to county council shake-up attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
District councils yesterday attacked the move by four county councils to
seek judicial review of the Local Government Commission's plans to
restructure them as a 'waste of time and taxpayers' money'.
The Labour-led Association of District Councils said that the counties were
'wasting public money on a lost cause'.
Ms Margaret Singh, who chairs the association, said: 'The commission's task
is difficult enough without the process being thrown into jeopardy by county
councils' delaying tactics, especially as they are squandering money which
could be put to better use.'
Cleveland and Somerset, which would both be abolished under the proposals,
and Derbyshire, which would lose control of the city of Derby and north-east
Derbyshire, have all announced plans to challenge the commission's plans in
court. All three claim that the commission has not carried out its work
correctly.
Lancashire, for which proposals have not yet been announced, is also seeking
a judicial review over the way the commission has interpreted its remit
following a change in its official guidance from ministers in September.
In Cleveland, where the county has estimated the cost of legal action at
about Pounds 150,000, Mr Bob Gibson, leader of Stockton borough council,
said he was satisfied that the commission's work had been carried out
fairly.
He described the legal move as a 'last desperate attempt at
self-preservation'.
Letters, Page 10
