FT  30 DEC 93 / US seeks to speed Nafta tariff cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US yesterday said it would soon begin talks with Mexico and Canada to
speed tariff reductions negotiated under the North American Free Trade
Agreement on such items as flat glass, foods, wine, bedding components, and
big household appliances, writes Nancy Dunne in Washington.
Tariffs are scheduled to be phased out over 15 years. However, the Clinton
administration has promised to accelerate reductions for products where the
Mexican or Canadian duty is substant-ially higher than the US tariff.
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, said the US, in most cases, would
request the reduction for non-controversial products.
Three rounds of tariff acceleration talks have already been held under the
US-Canada Free Trade Agreement, yielding accelerated duty reductions on
Dollars 9bn (Pounds 6bn) in two-way trade.
Trade officials will give priority to petitions received by January 21.
Petitions received by February 25 will be considered later in the year.
