FT  30 DEC 93 / Oil company faces shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nigeria's military government yesterday appointed a panel to reorganise the
scandal-plagued Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation, Reuter reports from
Lagos.
The 10-member panel would also examine the accounts of state-owned NNPC,
which oversees Nigeria's oil industry and has been rocked by fraud
allegations.
The corporation supervises the export of more than 1.5m barrels of oil a
day, earning about Dollars 10bn a year and accounting for more than 90 per
cent of Nigeria's foreign exchange income.
Nigerian newspapers have recently given prominence to a World Bank report
which said Dollars 2.1bn of oil revenue in 1990, when the Gulf crisis
boosted oil prices, was unaccounted for by the military government then in
power.
