<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / BBV ready to run Banesto: Senior managers lined up to take
over main divisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANCO Bilbao Vizcaya, Spain's largest privately owned commercial bank, was
yesterday preparing to assume management control of Banco Espanol de Credito
following the dismissal of the Banesto board by the Bank of Spain.
Nine or 10 senior BBV executives were being considered by BBV last night to
run Banesto's main divisions. Mr Alfredo Saenz, BBV vice-president, was
named by the central bank on Tuesday as Banesto president in place of Mr
Mario Conde. The Spanish Finance Ministry meanwhile confirmed that its
insurance authority had intervened in Banesto's insurance affiliate, La
Union y El Fenix, dismissing the board headed by Mr Conde, and appointing
three officials to run the group.
Ownership of Union y Fenix, one of the biggest insurers in Spain, was in the
process of being transferred by Banesto to AGF of France, which holds 24 per
cent of the Spanish company. Last night it was unclear whether the transfer
would go ahead on the terms negotiated by the dismissed board.
At Banesto, the new board faces a difficult task. According to estimates in
Madrid, the value of the bank's assets would be reduced by about Pta 400bn
(Pounds 1.9bn) if its loan and equity portfolios were revalued correctly.
That figure includes an estimated Pta 80bn shortfall in the bank's pension
fund.
Although Banesto had raised about Dollars 775m (Pounds 520m) this year with
the help of the US commercial bank JP Morgan, it had clearly not been enough
to satisfy the central bank. Two weeks ago, Mr Conde was warned to come up
with a solution but had been unable to find funds.
The BBV is close to the government and the Bank of Spain, both of which want
Banesto merged with a healthy big Spanish bank. Analysts in Madrid said they
expected many of Banesto's assets - its industrial holdings, its regional
banking affiliate, Banco Vitoria, and its controlling stake in Portugal's
Banco Totta &amp; Acores - to be sold off, with the BBV taking the rump of the
parent banking business. Absorption of Banesto would make the BBV Spain's
biggest bank but it would involve trimming branches.
A senior Bank of Spain official said inspectors had found that Banesto's
need to provide for pensions had risen from some Pta30bn last year to nearly
Pta80bn in October.
He added that capital gains in Banesto's industrial corporation had been
incorrectly booked. Banesto and the Bank of Spain have long been in dispute
about Banesto's treatment of portfolio losses. Bank officials accused Mr
Conde of taking profits or losses, whichever made Banesto's figures seem
favourable.
Mr Roberto Mendoza, the Morgan vice-chairman most closely associated with
Banesto, was in Madrid yesterday. Morgan decided its Corsair banking fund
should invest Dollars 175m in Banesto earlier this year.
Banesto crisis, Page 11
Editorial Comment, Page 11
Lex, Page 12
</TEXT>
