<HEADLINE>
FT  30 DEC 93 / Government to give funds for new selective schools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday announced that it would provide funds for new
selective grammar schools in a radical extension of its policy of
encouraging 'choice and diversity' in education.
This departure from the policy of building comprehensive schools, in force
for about 25 years, was immediately condemned by the Labour party.
Individual promoters, which the government expects will include parents,
religious interest groups and business organisations, will be allowed to
establish new schools, with 85 per cent of the capital building costs met by
the government. The balance must come from the promoters.
This is the same financial requirement that must currently be met by
churches when funding voluntary-aided schools. However, the new schools will
be grant-maintained and funded directly by the government, rather than by
local authorities.
Mr Robin Squire, the schools minister, said: 'Promoters may propose
different types of schools. For example, new grant-maintained schools may be
selective, or have partial selection. They could be single-sex or have a
single-sex stream.'
Existing independent schools which are in financial difficulties will also
be allowed to apply for grant-maintained status.
Methods of selection must be published, and approved by Mr John Patten, the
education secretary. Written academic examinations would be acceptable,
although the department stressed this did not mean a return to the '11-plus'
system. Schools will also be allowed to select pupils on the basis of
aptitude in specialisms, such as technology, music or dance.
Mrs Ann Taylor, Labour's education spokesman, said: 'Labour has consistently
warned that Mr Patten has a hidden agenda to reintroduce selective
education. Today that agenda has been made explicit.'
She said: 'Selective education favours the very few at the expense of the
vast majority. Children are labelled, often wrongly, with the majority being
classified as failures.'
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, said:
'The government is putting the education of the children of this country up
for grabs and it's not good enough. They are asking for money from industry
which it's probably unable to give.'
The measures are outlined in draft guidance for promoters, on which the
government has asked for comments by the end of next month. The draft refers
only to building new schools rather than converting existing schools.
According to the education department, there is a need for new schools in
the south-west, Hampshire and the south-east.
However, school administrators questioned this. The Association of County
Councils, which represents rural local education authorities, said it found
the announcement surprising as 'the secretary of state has been telling us
there are millions of surplus places in existing schools'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
