<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow reaches yet another
record high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Although US stock markets saw early selling yesterday, the losses were
relatively limited and share prices rebounded to end the day marginally
higher in record territory, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
By the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 0.83 at 3,793.76, a
new record close. The more broadly-based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended up 0.40
at 470.94, another all-time high, while the American Stock Exchange
composite index finished 2.84 higher at 470.00 and the Nasdaq composite up
3.51 at 764.57. Trading volume on the NYSE was 202m shares. Sentiment
remained positive as investors headed into the new year in an upbeat mood.
Trading, however, was subdued because many investors were away for an
extended holiday. Yesterday's early selling was to be expected, given the
extent of the market's gains the previous day.
On Monday, the Dow jumped 35.21 to a record high of 3,792.93, while the S &amp;
P 500 put on 3.16 at 470.54, also a record high. The Amex composite firmed
1.84 to 467.16 and the Nasdaq composite added 2.36 to end at 761.06. Trading
volume on Monday was 171m shares.
US share prices have been pushing ahead to new peaks because of several
factors. They include fresh evidence of the strengthening economy, strong
overseas markets, and signs that the Federal Reserve is not yet ready to
raise interest rates. Yesterday, investors received good news from the
Conference Board, which reported that its closely-followed index of consumer
confidence jumped to 80.2 in December, up from 71.9 in November. Sentiment
was also buoyed by fresh declines in commodity prices, including oil.
Among individual stocks, semiconductor issues were in demand on the news
that the Clinton administration had called for emergency talks on
semiconductor trade with Japan in the wake of figures showing a decline in
foreign companies' share of the Japanese semiconductor market. Motorola,
which was up more than Dollars 1 at one stage, rose Dollars 1/4 to Dollars
91 5/8 , Texas Instruments firmed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 63 1/8 , and
Intel, which is traded on the Nasdaq market, added Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars
64.
Cyclical stocks were in mixed form. Allied-Signal fell Dollars  1/4 to
Dollars 79 5/8 and International Paper eased Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 67 7/8
on profit-taking, but Caterpillar firmed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 90 1/4 and
Bethlehem Steel put on Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 19. Auto stocks remained in
good demand as investors bet that sales of new cars and trucks would stay
healthy throughout early 1994. Chrysler rose Dollars 5/8 to Dollars 53 7/8 ,
Ford put on Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 64 3/4 and General Motors firmed Dollars
 3/8 to Dollars 56 3/4 .
On the Nasdaq market, QVC Network fell Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 37 7/8 amid
reports that if it succeeds with its Dollars 10bn bid for Paramount
Communications it will be forced to take billions of dollars in goodwill
charges for the next 20 to 40 years.
Canada
TORONTO stocks were sharply higher in quiet trading. The TSE-300 composite
index rose 42.46 points, or 1.0 per cent, to 4,288.85. Advances led declines
461 to 230, volume of 35.49m shares was below Thursday's 59.9m and trading
value was CDollars 313.4m compared with CDollars 523.4m.
The market was closed last Friday and yesterday for the Christmas holiday.
</TEXT>
