<DATE>931229
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 93 / International Company News: Mitsubishi companies to merge
operations - Creation of Japan's biggest chemicals group could spark more
consolidations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Two Japanese chemical companies that belong to the Mitsubishi group of
companies plan to merge their operations in a move that will create the
largest chemical company in Japan.
Mitsubishi Petrochemical, the largest domestic petrochemical company in
which Shell Petroleum has a 12.6 per cent stake and Shell Japan a 5.7 per
cent stake, and Mitsubishi Kasei, the country's biggest all-round chemical
manufacturer, plan to merge next October on an equal basis.
The new company to be formed by the merger, Mitsubishi Chemical, will have
consolidated profits of more than Y1,000bn (Dollars 9.35bn) and a combined
share of more than 15 per cent of the domestic ethylene market.
The decision, aimed at increasing the companies' international
competitiveness, comes in the midst of one of the most difficult times for
Japan's petrochemical sector and is expected to encourage further
consolidation in the industry.
The country's chemical industry has not only suffered a prolonged business
slump in the domestic market, as leading customers in the auto, electronics
and construction industries have faced sharp declines in their businesses,
but is also facing growing competition overseas.
The problems of Japan's chemical manufacturers are not new. Overcapacity has
plagued the industry since the early 1980s and there have been persistent
rumours of consolidation for the past 10 years, according to Mr John
Chanoki, chemical industry analyst at James Capel.
After the first oil shock, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry
encouraged companies to join forces in sales co-operatives that were able to
control prices. Nevertheless, Japan's 14 chemical companies remained
fiercely independent and have, until now, managed to avoid full-scale
mergers.
But as the Mitsubishi companies' merger reflects, the worsening business
environment has made independence a luxury that many Japanese chemical
companies can no longer afford.
The slowdown of the domestic economy has hit Japan's chemical companies at a
particularly difficult time. Overcapacity at home has been compounded by a
loss of export markets in south-east Asia where the Japanese have faced
growing competition from other countries, particularly from South Korea.
At the same time, the move of their large customers in the automobile and
electronics industries to increase production overseas has hurt the ability
of Japanese chemical manufacturers, which have not followed their customers
abroad, to compete with more low-cost overseas producers for their
traditional business.
Both Mitsubishi Petrochemical and Mitsubishi Kasei are expected to report
pre-tax losses in the year to March, 1994.
Furthermore, the increasing reluctance of the Japanese authorities to
protect the chemical industry from outside competition makes their future
look grim as well.
With the successful conclusion of the Uruguay Round of the Gatt, Japanese
chemical makers will face tariff reductions on imported chemicals of, on
average, more than 50 per cent in five years' time.
Against this background of increasing competition both at home and abroad,
Japanese chemical companies are being forced to accept the necessity of
consolidation to create larger, more efficient and internationally
competitive businesses.
The seriousness of the situation is underlined by the merger of the two
Mitsubishi companies which, despite belonging to the same Mitsubishi group
of companies with ties that go back to the pre-war zaibatsu business groups,
were known for their intense rivalry.
Mitsubishi Kasei, for example, has its own corporate symbol which its uses
more prominently than the three-diamonds symbol of the Mitsubishi group.
Mitsubishi Petrochemical, meanwhile, has not joined certain study groups on
environmental issues in which Mitsubishi Kasei has taken leadership.
Analysts expect the decision by the two Mitsubishi companies to ease the way
for other mergers in the industry, with Mitsui Toatsu Chemicals and Mitsui
Petrochemicals, two companies in the Mitsui group, at the top of the
candidates' list.
Within the Mitsubishi group there are three more chemical companies, which
are also likely candidates for further consolidation of the group's chemical
businesses.
Whether or not such mergers will strengthen the Japanese industry's
international competitiveness, however, is open to debate.
Unless the merger of the two Mitsubishi companies is accompanied by bold
restructuring that includes personnel cuts, two bad companies will not make
a good one, says Mr Chanoki.
Furthermore, in an industry where scale is crucial, even the Mitsubishi
merger which will create Japan's largest chemical company, will not bring
Japan close to the ranks of the world's largest chemical companies such as
EI du Pont de Nemours and Dow Chemical of the US, and the UK's Imperial
Chemical Industries. By sales, Mitsubishi Chemical is unlikely even to reach
the ranks of the world's top 10 chemical companies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Mitsubishi Petrochemical.
    Mitsubishi Kasei Corp.
    Mitsubishi Chemical.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2869 Industrial Organic Chemicals, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
