<HEADLINE>
FT  29 DEC 93 / Ford set to dispatch full-time executives to help Mazda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mazda, the troubled Japanese carmaker, will accept three senior executives
from Ford, the US carmaker which is its largest shareholder, in a move aimed
at ensuring its long-term survival.
Ford has agreed to send three full-time executives, including a senior vice
president, to Mazda. The appointments will increase the number of Ford
executives at Mazda from one to four and the number of seats Ford has on
Mazda's 42-member board from four to seven.
Mr Yoshihiro Wada, Mazda's president, said the move - to be formally
approved at a shareholder meeting in June - aimed to extend co-operation in
areas such as product development and use of global facilities.
However, the appointment of high-level executives from Ford highlights the
difficulties Mazda faces amid economic slowdown in Japan and overcapacity in
other world markets.
The Ford appointments were announced alongside a revamp of top management at
Mazda, with five board members retiring and Mr Wada assuming responsibility
for domestic marketing and sales. The move ties in with recognition within
Mazda that as markets have become saturated, carmakers must co-operate to
survive.
Mazda is suffering from the twin burdens of an underused state-of-the-art
manufacturing plant, in which it invested heavily, and a large distribution
network. It expects to post a Y32bn (Pounds 200m) pre-tax loss for the year
to March and is restructuring to regain profitability.
Meanwhile, ambitions to set up a manufacturing facility in Europe were
quashed when a plan to use Ford's manufacturing facility there fell apart
earlier this year.
While no plans have been announced on how the two could co-operate further,
Mazda said it hoped independent tie-ups with Ford, such as Mazda's
production of Ford Festivas in Japan and Ford's manufacturing of the Navaho
for Mazda in the US, could be developed into more long-term arrangements.
</TEXT>
